# Infrastructure Standards

## External integrations
- Implement `IComputeProvider` / `IPodProvider` in `Infrastructure/RunPod/` (or future provider folders)
- Return strongly typed `Application.Models.*` DTOs — never expose raw JSON to Application
- Use `IHttpClientFactory` with named clients (`nameof(RunPodProvider)`)
- Map provider-specific status strings to domain enums in Infrastructure only

## Services
- `*Service` classes orchestrate provider factory + encryption + persistence
- Register provider implementations as singletons; orchestration services as scoped
- Decrypt API keys only inside Infrastructure, immediately before provider calls

## EF Core
- Register configurations via `ApplyConfigurationsFromAssembly`
- Use cascade delete from `Organization` → tenant-owned children
- Add `DbSet` + `IApplicationDbContext` queryables and named `Add*Async` / `Remove*Async` helpers
- Name migrations `Part{N}{Feature}` (e.g. `Part4Pods`)

## Background workers
- Extend `BackgroundService`; use `IServiceScopeFactory` per iteration
- Skip registration in `Testing` environment (match `ProviderHealthWorker` pattern)
- Per-item try/catch so one failure does not stop the batch
- Log structured events: sync completed, sync failed, health check

## SignalR
- Hubs in Infrastructure; broadcast via `IPodNotificationService`
- Group clients by organization: `org-{organizationId}`
- Support JWT via `access_token` query param for WebSocket connections

## Bug prevention
- Use `ApplyProviderStatus` for lifecycle ops; use full `ApplyProviderInfo` only on create/sync
- Persist pod + configuration in one save to avoid duplicate EF tracking
- Include `Provider.Credential` when handlers need decrypted keys
